  <!-- Q1 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q1</span><span class="q-cat cat-arch">Architecture</span>
      <span class="q-text">Why did you choose a star schema instead of a normalized (3NF) schema?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>Star schema reduces JOIN complexity for analytical queries. In a normalized schema, a simple revenue-by-category query might require 4-5 JOINs through product → subcategory → category tables. In a star schema, that's one JOIN from fact to dim_product since all product attributes are denormalized into one table. For a BI data warehouse where analysts run hundreds of queries daily, that performance gain is significant. The trade-off is some data redundancy — category name is repeated for every product — but storage is cheap and query speed matters more in this use case.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q2 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q2</span><span class="q-cat cat-arch">Architecture</span>
      <span class="q-text">Walk me through your partitioning strategy and why you chose year/month.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>I partitioned the fact_orders table by year and month on S3. When Athena runs a query like "show me Q3 revenue," it uses partition pruning to only scan the July, August, and September partitions — roughly 25% of the data instead of 100%. This reduces both query time and cost since Athena charges per terabyte scanned. I chose month-level granularity because the business's typical queries are month-over-month comparisons. Day-level partitioning would create too many small files, which hurts performance. The tradeoff is that cross-month queries still scan all relevant months, but that's acceptable for this use case.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q3 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q3</span><span class="q-cat cat-arch">Architecture</span>
      <span class="q-text">What's the difference between a surrogate key and a natural key? Which did you use?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>A natural key is the ID from the source system — like order_id = "ORD-A4B3C2D1". A surrogate key is a generated identifier that exists only in the warehouse. I used MD5 hashes of the source ID as surrogate keys. The benefit is decoupling — if the upstream order management system changes its ID format, our warehouse keys remain stable. It also helps when merging data from multiple source systems where the same business entity might have different IDs. The trade-off is a slight overhead for hashing, which is negligible at this scale.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q4 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q4</span><span class="q-cat cat-spark">PySpark</span>
      <span class="q-text">What is Adaptive Query Execution (AQE) and when did you enable it?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>AQE is a Spark 3.0+ feature that re-optimizes query plans at runtime based on actual statistics collected during execution. I enabled it with <code>spark.sql.adaptive.enabled = true</code>. Before AQE, Spark optimized the execution plan before the job ran, based on estimates that might be wrong. With AQE, it can dynamically coalesce shuffle partitions — if a shuffle produces 200 partitions but most are tiny, AQE merges them into fewer larger ones. It also handles skew joins by splitting oversized partitions. For this project it matters most for the LEFT JOIN between fact_orders and returns where the data size ratio is unpredictable.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q5 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q5</span><span class="q-cat cat-spark">PySpark</span>
      <span class="q-text">Why did you use coalesce(1) before writing the output?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p><code>coalesce(1)</code> merges all data partitions into one before writing, producing a single Parquet file per table. I did this for local development because the dataset is small — 5,000 orders. Multiple small Parquet files from different partitions create overhead. In production at scale, I would remove coalesce(1) or use repartition(n) with a reasonable number based on data size — typically targeting 128-256MB per file. The difference between coalesce and repartition: coalesce is a narrow transformation that only merges partitions without a full shuffle. repartition does a full shuffle and can both increase and decrease partition count. coalesce can only reduce partitions.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q6 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q6</span><span class="q-cat cat-spark">PySpark</span>
      <span class="q-text">Explain the difference between narrow and wide transformations. Give examples from your code.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>Narrow transformations process each row independently with no data movement between partitions. Examples from my code: <code>withColumn()</code>, <code>filter()</code>, <code>select()</code>, <code>cast()</code> — adding the order_date_ts column or filtering invalid rows are all narrow. Wide transformations require shuffling data across the network between executors. Examples from my code: <code>groupBy().agg()</code>, <code>dropDuplicates()</code>, and the <code>join()</code> between orders and returns. Wide transformations are expensive and create stage boundaries in Spark. That's why I kept the join as a LEFT JOIN rather than inner — fewer rows to shuffle, and I use <code>coalesce</code> only after all the wide operations are done.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q7 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q7</span><span class="q-cat cat-dq">Data Quality</span>
      <span class="q-text">How did you handle bad records — did you drop them or quarantine them?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>I quarantined them rather than dropping them. Dropping bad records silently is dangerous — you lose visibility into upstream data quality problems. My approach: I tagged each row with an <code>_is_valid</code> flag and a <code>_failed_checks</code> string listing which checks failed. Valid rows went to the processed fact table. Invalid rows went to a quarantine S3 path. This means I can monitor quarantine volume over time — if it spikes, that signals a source system issue. I also log the failure rate per check so the data engineering team can prioritize fixes with the upstream team. In a production pipeline I'd also fire a CloudWatch alert if the quarantine rate exceeds a threshold, like 5%.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q8 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q8</span><span class="q-cat cat-dq">Data Quality</span>
      <span class="q-text">How would you handle schema drift — what if the source adds a new column tomorrow?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>Schema drift is one of the trickiest real-world problems. My approach has three layers. First, for additive changes — new columns appearing — I use schema evolution support in Spark and Parquet with <code>mergeSchema = true</code>. New columns get added to the processed table automatically. Second, for breaking changes — column renamed or type changed — I add a schema validation step at ingestion that compares the incoming schema against the expected schema and fails fast with a clear error message before writing anything. Third, for production I'd implement schema registry using AWS Glue Data Catalog to version schemas and trigger alerts on unexpected changes. The key is never silently accepting a bad schema — fail loud and early rather than writing corrupted data downstream.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q9 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q9</span><span class="q-cat cat-sql">SQL</span>
      <span class="q-text">Explain the difference between RANK, DENSE_RANK, and ROW_NUMBER.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>All three assign numbers to rows in a sorted result, but they handle ties differently. <code>ROW_NUMBER()</code> gives every row a unique number regardless of ties — if two products have the same revenue, one gets rank 1 and the other gets rank 2 arbitrarily. <code>RANK()</code> gives tied rows the same rank but skips the next rank — two products tied at rank 1 means the next product gets rank 3, not rank 2. <code>DENSE_RANK()</code> gives tied rows the same rank with no gaps — two products tied at rank 1 means the next product gets rank 2. In my category ranking query I used DENSE_RANK because I didn't want to skip rank numbers when multiple categories were close in revenue. ROW_NUMBER is best for deduplication — picking one row when there are duplicates.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q10 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q10</span><span class="q-cat cat-sql">SQL</span>
      <span class="q-text">Walk me through your cohort retention query. What business question does it answer?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>The query answers: "Of customers who made their first purchase in January, what percentage came back to buy again in February, March, etc.?" This is the most important metric for an e-commerce subscription or repeat-purchase business. I built it in three steps. First CTE finds each customer's first-ever order month — their "cohort." Second CTE joins all orders back to that cohort month and calculates months_since_first for each subsequent purchase. The final SELECT uses FIRST_VALUE window function partitioned by cohort_month to grab the original cohort size, then divides each month's active customers by that cohort_size to get a retention percentage. A healthy e-commerce business typically sees 20-40% Month 1 retention. If you see it dropping to 5%, that's a product or customer experience issue — which ties directly to my background in customer experience operations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q11 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q11</span><span class="q-cat cat-prod">Production</span>
      <span class="q-text">How would you make this pipeline idempotent?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>An idempotent pipeline produces the same result no matter how many times you run it for the same input data. Right now my pipeline uses <code>write.mode("overwrite")</code> which is partially idempotent — re-running overwrites existing output. But for incremental loads, I need to be more careful. I'd implement idempotency by adding a processing_date column to track which batch each row came from, then using a DELETE WHERE processing_date = target_date followed by INSERT pattern — or better, using partition-level overwrite so Spark only overwrites the specific date partitions being processed. In Redshift or a proper database I'd use MERGE (upsert). I'd also add a pipeline run log table that records each run's status, so I can detect and re-run failed batches safely.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q12 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q12</span><span class="q-cat cat-prod">Production</span>
      <span class="q-text">How would this pipeline scale to 10 million orders per day?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>Several changes. First, move from a single Glue job to an EMR cluster with auto-scaling — more executor nodes for parallel processing. Second, remove coalesce(1) and let Spark use its natural parallelism, targeting 256MB per output file using <code>repartition()</code> based on data size. Third, switch from full table overwrites to incremental processing — only process new records using watermark timestamps or CDC (Change Data Capture) from the source database. Fourth, add a message queue like SQS or Kinesis between the source systems and the raw S3 zone so we can handle traffic spikes without losing data. Fifth, consider partitioning at day level instead of month level at that volume, since month partitions would be too large for efficient pruning. Finally, add a proper orchestrator like Apache Airflow or AWS Step Functions to manage retries, dependencies, and monitoring.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q13 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q13</span><span class="q-cat cat-arch">Architecture</span>
      <span class="q-text">What's the difference between batch processing and stream processing? When would you use each?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>Batch processing collects data over a period and processes it all at once — daily, hourly, or on a schedule. Stream processing ingests and processes data continuously, record by record or in micro-batches, with latency measured in seconds. I used batch processing for this project because the business question — "what was our revenue last month?" — doesn't require real-time data. Batch is simpler to build, cheaper to run, and easier to debug. I'd switch to stream processing if the requirement changed to real-time fraud detection (flag a suspicious transaction within 5 seconds), live inventory updates, or real-time personalization during a session. The key question is: what's the acceptable latency? If it's minutes or hours, batch. If it's seconds, stream. The cost and complexity of streaming is only justified when real-time actually changes a business decision.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q14 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q14</span><span class="q-cat cat-spark">PySpark</span>
      <span class="q-text">What is a broadcast join and when should you use it?</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-body">
      <div class="answer-label">Model Answer</div>
      <p>A broadcast join sends a copy of a small table to every executor node so the join can happen locally without shuffling the large table across the network. In my pipeline, if I'm joining a large fact_orders table with a small dim_date table (366 rows for a year), Spark should broadcast dim_date. I can hint this explicitly with <code>F.broadcast(dim_date)</code>. The rule of thumb is to broadcast tables under 10MB — configurable via <code>spark.sql.autoBroadcastJoinThreshold</code>. With AQE enabled, Spark will often detect small tables and broadcast automatically. Without broadcast, both tables get shuffled in a sort-merge join, which is expensive. This is one of the most common PySpark performance optimizations and comes up in almost every senior interview.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q15 -->
  <div class="q-card">
    <div class="q-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="q-num">Q15</span><span class="q-cat cat-prod">Production</span>
