<div class="section" id="section-concepts">
  <div class="hero">
    <div class="hero-tag">Key Concepts</div>
    <h1>Concepts to Understand Deeply</h1>
    <p>These are the theoretical foundations behind everything you built. Study one per day during Week 2.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
      <div class="step-num">📐</div>
      <div><div class="step-title">Star Schema vs Snowflake Schema</div></div>
      <div class="step-chevron">▼</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p><strong>Star Schema:</strong> Fact table at center, denormalized dimensions around it. One JOIN gets you from fact to any attribute. Used in this project. Best for: BI tools, analyst self-service, read-heavy workloads.</p>
      <p><strong>Snowflake Schema:</strong> Dimension tables are further normalized. dim_product → dim_subcategory → dim_category. Reduces storage redundancy but requires more JOINs. Best for: large cardinality dimensions, when storage matters more than query speed.</p>
      <p><strong>Interview rule:</strong> Star for analytics. Snowflake for very large, hierarchical dimensions. You'll see snowflake in healthcare (ICD codes have deep hierarchies) and finance.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
      <div class="step-num">⚡</div>
      <div><div class="step-title">Spark Execution Model</div></div>
      <div class="step-chevron">▼</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>Spark is lazy — when you write <code>df.filter()</code>, nothing happens. Spark builds a logical plan. When you call <code>df.count()</code>, <code>df.write()</code>, or <code>df.show()</code> — that's an action and triggers execution.</p>
      <p>The execution plan is broken into stages separated by shuffles (wide transformations). Within each stage, tasks run in parallel across partitions. Understanding this explains why you see "Stage 1 → Stage 2 → Stage 3" in the Spark UI.</p>
      <p><strong>Key terms to know:</strong> Driver, Executor, Partition, Stage, Task, Shuffle, DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
      <div class="step-num">🗜</div>
      <div><div class="step-title">Parquet + Columnar Storage</div></div>
      <div class="step-chevron">▼</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>CSV stores data row by row. Parquet stores data column by column. When Athena runs <code>SELECT SUM(net_revenue)</code>, it only reads the net_revenue column — skipping all other columns entirely. On a wide table with 50 columns, this can reduce I/O by 98%.</p>
      <p>Snappy compression (used in this project) compresses within each column. Since all values in a column have the same type and often similar values (e.g., order_status has only 3 distinct values), compression ratios are 3-10x better than gzip on CSV.</p>
      <p><strong>Parquet also stores statistics</strong> (min/max per column block), enabling Athena to skip entire row groups that don't match a WHERE clause — called predicate pushdown.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
      <div class="step-num">🪟</div>
      <div><div class="step-title">SQL Window Functions</div></div>
      <div class="step-chevron">▼</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>Window functions compute a value for each row based on a set of related rows (the "window") without collapsing rows like GROUP BY does.</p>
      <p>The anatomy: <code>FUNCTION() OVER (PARTITION BY col ORDER BY col ROWS/RANGE BETWEEN...)</code></p>
      <ul style="color:var(--text2); font-size:14px; padding-left:20px; margin-top:8px;">
        <li><strong>PARTITION BY</strong> — resets the window for each group (like GROUP BY but keeps all rows)</li>
        <li><strong>ORDER BY</strong> — determines row order within each partition</li>
        <li><strong>ROWS BETWEEN</strong> — frame specification (UNBOUNDED PRECEDING = from first row)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Functions used in this project: LAG (previous row), LEAD (next row), RANK/DENSE_RANK/ROW_NUMBER (ranking), FIRST_VALUE/LAST_VALUE (boundary values), SUM/AVG with frame (running totals).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
      <div class="step-num">📦</div>
      <div><div class="step-title">Batch vs Stream Processing</div></div>
      <div class="step-chevron">▼</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p><strong>Batch:</strong> Collect data → process all at once → write output. Latency: minutes to hours. Tools: PySpark (this project), dbt, AWS Glue. Best for: daily reports, historical analysis, ML training data.</p>
      <p><strong>Stream:</strong> Process each event as it arrives. Latency: milliseconds to seconds. Tools: Apache Kafka, Apache Flink, Spark Structured Streaming, AWS Kinesis. Best for: fraud detection, real-time dashboards, live inventory.</p>
      <p><strong>Micro-batch:</strong> Middle ground — batch every 30 seconds. Spark Structured Streaming default. Good when you need near-real-time but don't need true event-by-event processing.</p>
      <p><strong>Interview rule:</strong> Always ask "what's the acceptable latency?" before recommending stream vs batch. Stream is 10x more complex. Only justify it when latency changes a decision.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

